text: I'm sure everyone has seen it already, and even if you haven't it's not particularly interesting, but:

July 2017 Update

Banned List: No Changes

Rules: No Changes 

Banned List Announcement Clarification

Our friends in R&D have adopted an understandably aggressive approach to looking at the Banned and Restricted lists for other formats more often than we find necessary for Commander. As more of a clarification than a change, we’ll continue making our announcements quarterly, on the Monday after each pre-release. You’ll see updates from us 25 September 2017 (Ixalan) and 15 January 2018 (Rivals of Ixalan). Until then, here’s hoping you’re enjoying the new toys Hour of Devastation brings you.
fancy. Speaking of bans what cards do you guys think deserve a ban hammer? I personally think cyclonic rift is too good for the format. proof being it makes it into almost any blue deck.
I don't think Rift is too good necessarily. Every deck runs Sol Ring, too. Rift is super strong and I wouldn't shed a tear if they banned it, but I'm not sure such a banning is necessarily justified.
Vs Protean Hulk where both times I've seen it post-unbanning has turned into a clown fiesta of clones, etc. warping the entire game around it
i think it’s ok to have some cards that are good
it doesn’t win on the spot
it costs a lot of mana
and plenty of times i bounce something of my enemy’s that has some nasty etb effects

I'd argue the un-sung portion of what makes rift so strong is the option to cast it for 2. Unlike something like Insurrection that is dead in your hand a ton of times either because you don't have 8 mana or stuff worth stealing, I've seen multiple non-overloaded rifts save games. It's a blow-out card overloaded, but if you don't have overload mana it can still save your ass.

I think vs protean hulk you have to look at the fact that the deck has to designed to use it. Taking additional slots in order to take advantage. However, rift just fits in. It doesn't instantly win you the game though. It only sets you up to be several turns ahead of each opponent.

I have strong feelings on Cyclonic Rift, lol. But... I agree with <@U4V5EHQ2G> that I don't think a ban is "justified."
Same with Sol Ring. If Sol Ring/Crypt/Vault got banned I wouldn't shed a tear. That's more a personal gripe though, as every deck is 98 cards + Sol Ring. But, do they deserve it? Doubtful.

in both cases where I saw Hulk do stupid shit it wasn't even in decks built to abuse it. A friend slotted it into his beast tribal deck for the hell of it, and both times it went nuts were other people hitting him with Bribery.
<@U3FV90TCZ> Agreed, not sure I can justify those three rocks being banned but I'd be totally cool seeing it happen.
I will say that playing the multiplayer modo format for the last month has earned a love for not having fast mana
Removing the fast mana makes Rift that much better because opponents can't rebuild as fast.
It takes away the explosive starts that make one person take over. Most of the time the table teams up to slow them, but not having that made games more fun.
Nah. The fast mana is part of what makes Commander fun and it's available to everyone vs things like Rift or Hulk.
i use to be on the ban sol ring team, but i think randomly imbalanced games are fun. tables of 4 should self regulate most of the time and the added variance change games
sometime someone gets magical christmas land and wins on turn 3 or whatever because of fast mana, but shuffle up and play again? whats the big deal
Mostly. Crypt is pretty price prohibitive for a whole lot of people, and unlike duals or something it can wildly swing a game
Mana Vault is $15 which isn't nothing, either.
A lot of powerful cards aren't cheap - do we ban all expensive but powerful cards?
No, just saying they're not "available" to everyone
I meant by mana requirements. Not everything is available to everyone in the world.
I have one Mana Crypt that I pulled from Eternal Masters, but I'm not paying for one.
I think at $15 mana vault is still in the range though. I think banning expensive cards isn't a good approach either, also wizards states they don't know about the second market and so so.
I don't run Crypt or Vault in any decks at this point
range of reprint*
Becasue most in my meta don't, but that's neither here nor there
Regardless, like I said I don't really think they're bannable, it just wouldn't bug me if they were, same with Rift. I get the arguments, even if I don't neccessarily agree.

I used to be on team ban Rift, but honestly it's been in the format so long and folks know it's there but it doesn't really warp the meta. You have those Baral or Azami combo decks that use it to wipe the board for their combo turn but that's life.
banning for cost reasons is silly
its not a valid argument
it’s what makes magic what magic is. collecting for me is a major part of it
I agree because in many cases the price is for artificial scarcity reasons vs power.
It is a collectible card game.
It's in the name.

I agree, I just think that when you say "everyone can use Crypt" it's not entirely accurate. Yeah, every deck can, but not every player can get one. That isn't an argument to do anything based on that, mind you. Just pointing it out.
actually that might be the main reason i like EDH. I love the collectible aspect of the game and ive been playing a long time and it pays off. EDH lets me show off my cool / expensive old cards
(Notice I'm being good and not tilting Jason by mentioning the Reserve List)
I don't run proxies, and I don't swap cards between decks specifically because I like the collectible aspect
People are funny. I heard someone this weekend say they don't like Commander because they don't want 1 of a card - they want 4.
hehe
I love the singleton aspect - it makes for much more interesting build challenges.
If I want a Cradle in every deck I better pick one up for every deck, or decide where to run it. I don't expect anyone else to conform to that though.
Nope. Cradle is a card that is either fantastic or dead...especially after a Cyclonic Rift.
:stuck_out_tongue_winking_eye:
It also kinda feels bad to win with
At least it does for me
Like I'm the asshole buying wins
There's nothing remotely satisfying tapping Cradle for 9 to Biomass Mutation the table in Edric on turn 5.
It's all in how and when you use it. Are you playing against a bunch of precons and you whip out your tunes Edric deck with Cradle and win turn 2 or 3? Then you bought a win and are an a-hole.
Edric is my "fuck you" deck nowadays.

When someone is being a douchebag. Last time I played it was to kill a guy, then cast a spell, counter my own spell with Pact, then not pay the upkeep on purpose so he knew without a doubt I was just playing to kill him.
I had ran Cradle in a much softer Rith superfriends deck for awhile though and it just felt bad there in a casual deck.

I dunno, my favorite line I ever was the target of was when I was playing Rafiq and was accused of "only (winning) because I play expensive cards..." That card was Rest In Peace while it was still in standard.
Aside from Rafiq and lands you can probably build a pretty gross deck with no card over a dollar
Edric too really
one time someone t1'd a [[Hedron Crab]]

text: Speaking of Legends, I just got offered a Mirror Universe for a Consecrated Sphinx, Nahiri, Reanimate, Tooth and Nail and Yawgmoth's Will. I don't need a Mirror Universe at all, and I could see Yawg's Win going up more, but that feels like a deal I can't pass up.
Sure. I'm not sure why that's banned.
the original banning was said because of $
So for bad reasons.
which is funny because of how inconsistent they were on $ rulings
Immediately unban all $ bannings.
on the fast mana discussion, i’m for unbanning moxs and black lotus
Lotus for sure feels too strong, but there's certainly an inconsistency with the Mox being banned and Sol Ring/Crypt being okay
sol ring and mana crypt might be better than those cards
Yep
the only argument i saw for the moxs which i think were good… was that multi-color decks have advantage
but that’s true with mana rocks etc, so idk

You do then further stratify the moneyed players from the not. Now you've got Crypt and maybe Grim Monolith, but when you add a couple Mox and a Lotus that's a lot more rocks the guy with cash can slap down on turn 1/2. That said I think those kind of problems are a bit self-regulating. People who can afford or have the mox and would put them in a deck just aren't gonna be looking to pubstomp randos with precons.
:tophat:
The other argument is the banned moxen have no downsides. Crypt, Vault, etc have downsides. Sol Ring naturally doesn't.

To an earlier point: I've met some tonedeaf players who can't tell when or why their opponents are having zero fun against their hyper-tuned decks that play Ravages of War and other pricey BS. There are plenty of people with expensive cards who like to win against new and casual players, just for the sake of winning. 

If there's a self-correcting element, it's that the more casual players will try to avoid those competitive players, rather than the competitive players deciding not to stomp on casual players
This is my experience, at least

Those dudes certainly exist. I think there's an element of them being so goddamn obnoxious that they stand out in a way that makes it seem like it happens more frequently than it does, but it certainly happens.
That's also a good point:point_up:
Should the format allow for those type of players? Even one person could a large turn off to new players.
And you're right that when it self-corrects its the lower-powered players not playing with them anymore and rarely the inverse
Banning people is rarely the answer.
Also impossible...
The way they play the game is valid. It just doesn't match other players' goals. That's not a sin. It's just tonedeaf
Well I'm not sure banning people is rarely the answer. There's a lot of super broken people out there :slightly_smiling_face:
lol I'm not suggesting we ban people....just the method in which they're capable of being disruptive to playgroups and newer players.
See also November 8, 2016
I don't know if there's a way to police that you can bake into bans or anything
It would involve massive regulations. Basically turning EDH in to standard/modern feeling with the restrictions
Douchebags gonna douche.
Which I would not be a fan of

Insulating entire playgroups against a player/mindset doesn't really work either though. If it's a social format then people should be social, communicate before hand. Then you won't have to worry as much with people coming out of nowhere to kick the shit out of some baby seals
I mean Sheldon flat out said, "spikes go away, we don't want you to play this format."
Ps we've ban a player from the store before. Only after he played 8 myr enforcers in mirrodin standard though.
Plus, if someone is super competitive to a group of casuals, it took them all of 4 minutes to learn that dude is a combo player and that he's not fun to play with.
liking expensive cards is not the same as a spike
And even if you are spike, being one doesn't mean you don't have the ability to read the room and adjust accordingly
Most people have several different decks, you don't have to keep them all tuned to max power level
I sure as hell don't.
I guess from my experience spikes only become a problem when they are new to the group. If they've been identified by the group beforehand the games rarely go in their favor.
Maybe there should some kind of etiquette guide to playing with strangers.
My rule of thumb is start with a soft deck
i have decks i play with strangers when im feeling them out
Same
for example, my kozilek TGD deck i was talking about yesterday… that i felt could better fit that purpose without annihilator
Like I said earlier, just communicate before hand is always the easier way
"Cool, thanks for letting me join. What types of decks are we playing?" - Saves so many dirty looks later

We did have a situation a couple months ago though where a new player came to the shop and sat with myself and another guy and told us to take it easy on him since he was playing a new precon. Literally right in front of him we discussed which decks we'd play, dug out our weaker ones, etc. He was playing Ydris I think, and stormed out and killed the other guy on like turn four. He straight up lied about the deck.
But that shit is pretty rare.
Scummy folks gonna scum

That was the guy I Edric'ed. And proceeded to just do that in like the next five games, even after he tried to get away from me and find different pods. I pretty much devoted my night after that to killing him. Which is admittedly super petty, but fuck him.
Some of the best joys are the pettiest ones though.
moral of the story: don't fuck with dana

On the opposite end of the spectrum about a year ago we had a guy come in with a foiled out Rhys the Redeemed deck. Full suite of off-color Expedition fetches, etc. He played a foil Elesh Norn at one point and I jokingly asked why he didn't have the phyrexian judge foil, and he said he didn't know about it, so he pulled out his phone and bought one on eBay right there. Then next turn played a Moat when literally everyone but him had fliers in play.
Dollars gonna purchase
It was just super bizarre. He played probably four games and lost all four badly with this three thousand dollar deck.
Super nice guy too
I think at one point he cast a black-border Natural Selection
Wut...
Reminds me of a buddy that plays a [[sol'kanar the swamp king]] deck that plays all Arabian nights mountains and ptk3 cards. Deck is worth a ton and fun, but it's not that great.
